            <div type="typology">
               <head>Typology (Local)</head>
               <p rend="typology" xml:space="preserve">West (Maghreb) › Tunisia › North Western Tunisia</p>
               <p>Bedouin-type dialect</p>
            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <p xml:space="preserve">The ruins of ancient Thugga are a World Heritage Site according to UNESCO who characterises it as "the best preserved example of an Africo-Roman town in North Africa" 
               (<ref target="https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/794/">https://whc.unesco.org/en/list/794/</ref>). Like the whole region, Dougga was home to different civilisations like the Numidians/Berber, Punics, Romans, Byzantines, and finally the Arabs – all of whom have left their traces at the site (like the Lybico-Punic Mausoleum, the Numidian Temple of Massinissa, the Roman Capitol and several temples, the Byzantine citadel, etc.). After a prosperity period around the 3<sup>rd</sup> century AD, it seems to have fallen into decline but stayed populated even after the Muslim conquest, which is attested by a small mosque built in the Temple of August Piety. Only after the Tunisian independence in 1956, the last people inhabiting the archaeological site of Dougga (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">Dugga</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i"> l-</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">aṯā</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ṛ</hi>) were relocated to a close-by village, now called “New Dougga” (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">D</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ugga</hi> <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ž-</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ždīda</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">)</hi>. Local farmers report to still find Roman coins when ploughing the soil. The inhabitants of Dougga live on agriculture (mainly wheat and olives), animal husbandry (cows, sheep, goats and chicken) and apiary (for medical use). The traditional Tunisian bread (<hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">xubz</hi> <hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">il-g</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ō</hi><hi xml:lang="aeb" rendition="#i">ža</hi>) of Dougga is said to be very famous. </p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <p xml:space="preserve">To the best of our knowledge hitherto no research has been done on the dialect of Dougga, however this dialect is linguistically investigated within the TUNOCENT project.</p>
            </div>
